\section{Capability gate rules}{


Registration-time enforcement prevents an adapter from claiming a
capability without the hooks to back it. The rules are:
\itemize{
\item \code{component_significance} requires \code{null_action}, \code{component_stat},
\strong{and} \code{residualize}.
\item \verb{(cross, predictive, component_significance)} additionally
requires \code{refit}, \code{predict_response}, and a split-aware
\code{component_stat(..., split = NULL)}. This is the predictive
cross-fit admissibility rule: in-sample predictive significance
is refused at registration time.
\item \code{variable_stability} requires a perturbation path — \code{refit},
\code{bootstrap_action}, or both \code{core} and \code{update_core} — \strong{and} one of
\code{variable_stat} or \code{loadings}.
\item \code{score_stability} requires a perturbation path, \code{loadings}, and
either \code{scores} or \code{project_scores}.
\item \code{subspace_stability} requires a perturbation path \strong{and} \code{loadings}.
\item \code{variable_significance} is excluded from v1 and fails at
registration time with a reference to Part 5 §38.
}

Claiming a capability without the backing hooks is an error at
\code{\link[=infer_adapter]{infer_adapter()}} time, not at inference time. That is the point
of the gate: strict dispatch refuses to build an adapter that
cannot back up its claims.
}

\section{Geneig rule}{


Geneig adapters carry one extra registration-time rule. If an
adapter claims \verb{(geneig, generalized_eigen, component_significance)},
its constructor must set \code{geneig_deflation = "b_metric"} when the
\code{residualize} hook performs B-metric deflation itself, or
\code{geneig_deflation = "delegated"} when \code{run_geneig_ladder()} owns
the deflation. Euclidean residualization is not admissible for the geneig
family; the gate fails immediately with a pointer to
\code{notes/engine_geneig_spec.md}.
}

\section{Executable validity contracts}{


Every adapter also carries two assumption layers:

\describe{
\item{\code{declared_assumptions}}{A character vector of assumptions
the adapter \strong{declares} but does not check (e.g.
\code{"rows_exchangeable"}, \code{"centered_data"}). These are
trust-the-user claims that appear in the result's
\code{assumptions$declared} block for transparency.}

\item{\code{checked_assumptions}}{A list of \strong{executable} validity
checks. Each entry is a list with \code{name} (character), \code{check}
(function taking the raw \code{data} argument and returning a
logical, a character error message, or a \code{list(passed, detail)}
structured result), and \code{detail} (character fallback message).
\code{\link[=infer]{infer()}} runs every check against the input data before the
engine starts; strict mode errors on any failure, permissive
mode records the failures in \code{result$assumptions$checked}.}
}

The base-R reference adapters in \code{R/adapter_oneblock_baser.R} and
\code{R/adapter_cross_baser.R} populate \code{checked_assumptions} with the
standard set for their shape family — numeric-matrix check, finite
values, minimum dimensions, paired-row agreement, column variance,
and full column rank. Third-party adapters can reuse those helpers
or write their own.
}

\section{A minimal worked example}{


The smallest realistic one-block adapter is
\code{\link[=adapter_svd]{adapter_svd()}}, which wraps \code{base::svd} and claims all four
targets. See \code{R/adapter_oneblock_baser.R} for the full source.
The cross-family reference is \code{\link[=adapter_cross_svd]{adapter_cross_svd()}} in
\code{R/adapter_cross_baser.R}, which demonstrates the paired-row
contract and the relation-aware \code{component_stat} path.

For a fitted-model wrapper (the recommended pattern when you
already have a fitting framework, e.g. multivarious), see
\code{\link[=adapter_multivarious_pca]{adapter_multivarious_pca()}} and \code{\link[=adapter_multivarious_plsc]{adapter_multivarious_plsc()}} —
these are thin shims that delegate every hook to the underlying
multivarious generics (\code{components}, \code{coef}, \code{project}, etc.)
and cost only a few dozen lines each.
}

\section{Recommended pattern for new adapters}{

\enumerate{
\item Start from the adapter reference example closest to your
shape family (\code{adapter_svd} for oneblock, \code{adapter_cross_svd}
for cross).
\item Replace the fitting body of \code{refit} with a call into your
package's own fitter. Keep the return-value shape compatible
with your \code{loadings}, \code{scores}, and \code{roots} hooks.
\item Populate \code{checked_assumptions} with concrete checks that catch
the failure modes that matter for your method. Reuse
\code{.oneblock_baser_checks()} or \code{.cross_baser_checks()} when they
apply.
\item Add your adapter to the registry via
\code{\link[=register_infer_adapter]{register_infer_adapter()}} — typically from a zero-argument
function called by your package's \code{.onLoad} hook.
\item Write an integration test that calls \code{\link[=infer]{infer()}} with your
adapter id and a synthetic fixture.
}

If your fitted-model class already lives in another package (e.g.
you are writing an adapter for someone else's fitter), you do not
need to vendor the fitter into your code — just import the classes
you need and delegate the hooks.

For multiblock fits, declare \code{geometry = "multiblock"} and pass
list-of-matrix data with aligned rows through \code{refit()}, \code{null_action()},
\code{component_stat()}, and \code{residualize()}. The generic multiblock ladder
preserves block-list data; it does not flatten blocks internally. That
keeps MFA/JIVE/AJIVE-style refit semantics under adapter control.
}

